*starter solution
The "starter solutions technique" is a pesticide application method that involves spraying a small amount of
concentrated pesticide solution onto a small area of the crop, usually the base of the plant or the surrounding
soil. This concentrated solution is referred to as the "starter solution."
The purpose of this technique is to provide an initial dose of the pesticide to the plant or soil, which can then
spread throughout the plant or soil system over time. This can help to ensure that the pesticide is evenly
distributed and has a better chance of effectively controlling the target pest.
To use the starter solution technique, a small amount of concentrated pesticide solution is mixed with water to
create the desired spray solution concentration. The solution is then applied to the base of the plant or the
surrounding soil using a low-pressure spray nozzle or similar equipment.
It is important to use caution when applying pesticides and to follow all label instructions and safety
guidelines. Always wear appropriate protective equipment and avoid spraying in windy or rainy conditions.
Additionally, be sure to properly dispose of any unused pesticide solution and containers.
It refers to the application of solution of N, P2O5 and K2O in the ratio of 1:2:1 and 1:1:2 to young plants at
the time of transplanting, particularly for vegetables.
Starter solution helps in rapid establishment and quick growth of seedlings.
The disadvantages of starter solutions are
(i) Extra labour is required, and
(ii) the fixation of phosphate is higher.
